// ====SUMMARY====

// Git:
//
// - Distributed Version Control System (VCS)
// - Tracks project changes, allows reverting back to an older version
// - Enables collaboration and merging work

// GitHub:
// - Online platform built on Git
// - Provides an easy interface for collaboration
// - Hosts repositories, profiles, and community

// GitHub Flow:
// - Lightweight workflow for collaboration
// - Key elements:
//   * Repositories: Project folders with files & history
//   * Cloning: Copy repo locally for editing
//   * Committing: Save changes with messages
//   * Pushing: Upload commits to remote repo

// Important Terms:
// - Branches: Create separate workspaces for new features/experiments
// - Forks: Copy another repo to contribute or experiment freely
// - Pull Requests: Propose and review changes before merging
// - Issues: Track tasks, bugs, and enhancements
// - Profile: Showcase work and contributions
// - Markdown: Used for styling docs, READMEs, and comments

// Community Interaction:
// - Starring repositories: Bookmark and recommend projects
// - Following users: See their activity and discover projects
// - GitHub Explore: Find projects, events, and people

// Next Steps (Optional):
// - Create pull requests to share progress
// - Practice using markdown
// - Create profile README
// - Open new repos to explore GitHub features

// Resources:
// - Official GitHub docs, videos, and learning labs
// - Community forums for support and collaboration
